  "prompt": "What do doctors think when a patient dies?",
  "response": "When a patient dies, doctors typically experience a range of complex emotions and thoughts, which can vary depending on the individual doctor, circumstances of death, and their personal experiences. Some common reactions include:\n\n1. Professional emotions\n- Sadness\n- Sense of loss\n- Empathy for the patient's family\n- Questioning if everything possible was done\n\n2. Reflective thoughts\n- Reviewing the medical treatment\n- Analyzing potential missed opportunities\n- Considering alternative treatment approaches\n- Assessing medical decisions\n\n3. Emotional responses\n- Grief\n- Frustration\n- Self-doubt\n- Emotional exhaustion\n\n4. Psychological processing\n- Potential feelings of failure\n- Coping with professional limitations\n- Maintaining emotional distance\n- Seeking support from colleagues\n\n5. Ethical considerations\n- Ensuring end-of-life care was compassionate\n- Respecting patient dignity\n- Understanding medical limitations\n\n6. Potential follow-up actions\n- Discussing case with medical team\n- Potential morbidity and mortality review\n- Supporting patient's family\n- Personal reflection and self-care\n\nThese reactions are highly individual and can depend on factors like experience, specialization, personal resilience, and specific circumstances surrounding the patient's death.",
